        }
      }))
    }
  ]
};
---

<IndividualPageLayout
    title={seoTitle}
    description={seoDescription}
    schema={pageSchema}
    pageTitle={pageTitle}
    heroImage="/oscar/media/titanium-aerospace-jet-engine-testing-hero.webp"
    heroImageAlt="Titanium aerospace jet engine undergoing a high-performance ground test with active exhaust"
    faqSectionTitle="Frequently Asked Questions: Cold Forging"
    faqItems={faqs}
    ctaTitle="Request Quote For Cold Forging"
    ctaDescription=""
    sourcesTitle="Sources"
    sourcesList={sources}
    resourcesTitle="Our Internal Resources for Die Casting, Investment casting, Forging and Sand Casting"
    resourcesList={internalResources}
>

    <div slot="full-width" class="individual-content">

        <section id="overview" >
            <div class="content-container">
                
                <h2>Cold Forging: High-Volume Precision & Strain-Hardened Strength</h2>

                <div class="grid gap-10 lg:grid-cols-2 lg:items-center mt-6">
                    <div>
                        <p>
                           ForceBeyond is a premier manufacturer of high-precision cold forged components. 
                           By shaping metal at room temperature—well below its recrystallization point—cold forging uniquely alters the metal's 
                           internal structure through strain hardening. This process yields components with exceptional tensile strength, 
                           brilliant surface finishes, and incredibly tight dimensional tolerances.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Engineered for high-volume, high-speed production, our cold forging capabilities provide a highly economical solution for 
                            producing near-net and true net-shape parts. From intricate automotive fasteners to high-conductivity copper electronic components, 
                            ForceBeyond delivers fully finished, assembly-ready parts that frequently require zero secondary machining.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="relative">
                        <div class="overflow-hidden">
                            <img
                                src="/oscar/media/custom-cold-forged-metal-parts-fasteners-shafts-4k.webp"
                                alt="Custom cold-forged metal parts, including threaded fasteners, pins, shafts, studs, and precision components, on a fully white background."
                                class="w-full h-auto object-cover hover:scale-105 transition-transform duration-500"
                            />
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

            </div>
        </section>

        <section id="technical-capabilities" >
            <div class="content-container">
                <h2>Technical Capabilities: Cold Forging Materials</h2>
                    <p>
                        Because the metal is not softened by heat, cold forging requires highly ductile materials that can withstand extreme compressive 
                        forces without fracturing. ForceBeyond specializes in cold-forming the following alloy groups:
                    </p>
                    <div class="content-table-wrapper">
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th scope="col">Material Category</th>
                                <th scope="col">Common Alloys</th>
                                <th scope="col">Key Cold Forging Characteristics</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>

                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <th scope="row">Carbon & Low-Alloy Steels</th>
                                <td>1008, 1010, 1018, 1035</td>
                                <td>Highly ductile. Excellent for high-strength fasteners, pins, and small automotive shafts.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <th scope="row">Aluminum Alloys</th>
                                <td>1100, 6061, 7075</td>
                                <td>Exceptional malleability. Ideal for lightweight structural brackets and aerospace rivets.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <th scope="row">Copper & Brass</th>
                                <td>C11000, C26000</td>
                                <td>Supreme conductivity and cold-flow properties. Widely used for electronic terminals and heat sinks.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <th scope="row">Stainless Steel</th>
                                <td>302, 304, 410, 430</td>
                                <td>Requires higher press tonnages but yields highly corrosion-resistant, sterile medical and marine hardware.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div> 
            </div>
        </section>

        <section id="why-forcebeyond" >
            <div class="content-container">
                <h2>Why Partner with ForceBeyond for Cold Forging?</h2>
                
                <p>
                    When part volumes are high and designs allow for room-temperature deformation, 
                    cold forging is often the most mechanically superior and cost-effective manufacturing method available.
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Strain Hardening (Work Hardening):</strong>Unlike hot forging or casting, deforming metal at room temperature permanently compresses and elongates the grain structure. This drastically increases the metal's yield strength and hardness, allowing you to use a cheaper, lower-carbon steel to achieve high-strength results..
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Net-Shape Accuracy:</strong>Cold forging achieves the tightest dimensional tolerances of any bulk deformation process. Many parts come off the press at their exact final dimensions (net shape), completely eliminating the cost and time of CNC machining.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Superior Surface Finish:</strong>Because the metal is not exposed to extreme heat, there is no oxidation or scaling on the surface. Parts emerge with a smooth, bright finish that is immediately ready for plating or assembly.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Maximum Material Efficiency:</strong>The cold forging process (which includes upsetting, extrusion, and coining) simply moves metal rather than cutting it away. This results in near-zero material scrap, significantly driving down per-part costs on high-volume runs.
                    </li>
                </ul>
                
            </div>
        </section>
        <section id="cold-forging-process">
            <div class="content-container">
                <h2>
                    The Cold Forging Process: Extrusion & Upsetting
                </h2>
                <p>
                    Cold forging typically utilizes a progression of closed dies in a high-speed press. ForceBeyond leverages several specific cold forming techniques:
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Forward Extrusion:</strong>Forcing the metal through a die orifice to decrease its diameter and increase its length (ideal for shafts and pins).
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Backward Extrusion:</strong>Forcing metal to flow backward around a descending punch to create hollow, cup-shaped components.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Upsetting(Heading)</strong>Compressing the end of a metal rod to increase its diameter, which is the primary method used to create the heads of bolts, screws, and custom fasteners.
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section id = "Tier-1.5-integration">
            <div class="content-container">
                <h2>Tier-1.5 Integration: Complete Component Finishing</h2>
                <p>
                    While cold forging frequently eliminates the need for heavy machining, 
                    ForceBeyond operates on a Tier-1.5 model to ensure your parts are 100% assembly-ready when they arrive.
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Thread Rolling:</strong>Rather than cutting threads (which weakens the metal), we roll threads onto cold-forged fasteners, further strain-hardening the thread profile for maximum stripping resistance.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Micro-Machining:</strong>For highly complex features (like cross-holes or tight internal grooves) that cannot be pressed, our high-speed CNC centers provide finishing touches.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Plating & Coating:</strong>Zinc plating, nickel plating, chromate conversion, and anodizing to enhance the aesthetic and corrosion-resistant properties of the raw forged surface.
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section id="certified-applications" >
            <div class="content-container">
                <h2>Certified Cold Forging Applications</h2>
                
                <p>
                    ForceBeyond’s high-speed cold heading and forging presses supply millions of high-strength components to:
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Automotive & Transportation:</strong>Custom bolts, seatbelt mechanism pins, steering components, and spark plug shells.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Consumer Electronics:</strong>Heat sinks, highly conductive copper terminals, and precision casing screws.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Fluid & Air Control:</strong>Custom hose fittings, valve stems, and pneumatic couplings.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Construction & Hardware:</strong>High-tensile structural fasteners, concrete anchors, and specialized rivets.
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </section>
        
    </div>
</IndividualPageLayout>